T1  - International cooperation and exchange rate stabilization
AU  - Laskar, Daniel
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 21
IS  - 1
SP  - 151
EP  - 164
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/08/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(86)90011-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199686900115
AB  - We show that exchange rate stabilization can be viewed as a public good. Consequently, when countries do not coordinate their economic policies, the exchange rate fluctuates more than in the case of international cooperation. We consider a quite standard two-country model where the policymakers of each country have at their disposal one policy instrument, the money stock, and want to reduce the fluctuations of both the domestic output and the domestic price level. Then, we compare the non-cooperative Nash equilibrium to the set of Pareto optima. Our analysis provides a formal argument for some exchange rate stabilization.
ER  - 

